olive oil
3 clove garlic
40 g butter
1 packet jasmine rice
¼ tsp salt
1 parsnip
1 carrot
½ lemon
1 packet beef strips
½ packet tomato paste
1 tin coconut milk
1 sachet beef-style stock powder
1 tsp brown sugar
1 bag salad leaves
1.25 cup water (for the rice)
1 sachet Mumbai Spice Blend
¼ cup water (for the curry)

Preheat oven to 220°C/200°C fan-forced. Finely
chop garlic. In a medium saucepan, heat the
butter with a drizzle of olive oil over medium heat.
Cook 1/2 the garlic until fragrant, 1-2 minutes.
Add water (for the rice) and the salt to the pan
and bring to the boil. Add jasmine rice, stir, cover
with a lid and reduce heat to low. Cook for
12 minutes, then remove from heat and keep
covered until the rice is tender and water is
absorbed, 10-15 minutes.

TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam so
don't peek!

While the rice is cooking, cut parsnio and carrot
into bite-sized chunks. Place veggies on a lined
oven tray. Drizzle with olive oil, season with salt
and pepper and toss to coat. Spread out evenly,
then roast until tender, 20-25 minutes. Meanwhile,
zest lemon to get a pinch, then slice into wedges.

Little cooks: Kids can help wash and toss the
veggies!

In a large frying pan, heat a drizzle of olive oil
over high heat. When oil is hot, cook beef strips
in batches, tossing, until browned and cooked
through, 1-2 minutes. Transfer to a plate.

TIP: Cooking the meat in batches over a high heat
helps keep it tender.

When the veggies have 10 minutes cook time
remaining, return the frying pan to medium-high
heat with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook Mumbai
spice blend, tomato paste (see ingredients) and
remaining garlic until fragrant, 1 minute. Add
coconut milk, beef-style stock powder and water
(for the curry) and stir to combine. Bring to the
boil, then reduce heat to low-medium. Simmer
until curry has reduced slightly, 5-6 minutes.

Add beef strips and roast veggies to the curry
and cook until heated through, 1-2 minutes.
Add the brown sugar, salad leaves, lemon
zest, remaining butter and a generous squeeze
of lemon juice. Cook, stirring, until leaves have
wilted. Season with pepper.

Little cooks: Easy peasy, lemon squeezy! Kids can
squeeze the lemon juice over the curry.

Divide garlic rice between bowls and top with
Mumbai coconut beef curry. Serve with any
remaining lemon wedges.